<!-- ===== NUTRITION PAGE ===== -->
<div class="page" id="page-nutrition">
  <div class="page-header">
    <h1>Nutrition guide</h1>
    <p>The fundamentals that make the meal plan and workout actually work</p>
  </div>

  <div class="section-heading">Core principles</div>
  <div class="info-grid" style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
    <div class="info-card">
      <h3>Calorie target</h3>
      <p>Aim for <strong>1,500 cal/day</strong> — roughly a 400–500 calorie deficit from your maintenance level. This pace produces about 1 lb of fat loss per week without tanking your energy for workouts.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="info-card">
      <h3>Protein priority</h3>
      <p>Hit <strong>~150g protein per day</strong>. At 47 with 5 days of training, protein is what preserves muscle as the fat drops. Without it, you lose both — and your metabolism slows with the muscle loss.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="info-card">
      <h3>Carb timing</h3>
      <p>Eat most of your carbs <strong>at lunch</strong> when you're still active. Keep dinner lower in carbs and higher in protein and vegetables. Your body handles carbs better earlier in the day.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="info-card">
      <h3>Meal prep rule</h3>
      <p>Cook proteins on <strong>Sunday and Wednesday</strong>. If food is ready to go, you won't reach for something high-calorie when you're hungry. The plan only works when food is accessible.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section-heading">What to avoid</div>
  <div style="background: var(--white); border: 1px solid var(--gray-border); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: 4px 18px; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
    <ul class="avoid-list">
      <li><span class="dot-red"></span><strong>Sweet tea</strong> — your biggest culprit. 3–4 glasses = 150–300 empty sugar calories daily. Cut it or halve the sugar when you brew.</li>
      <li><span class="dot-red"></span><strong>Liquid IV overuse</strong> — one packet/day is fine. Multiple packets means 1,000–1,500mg of sodium from drinks alone before any food.</li>
      <li><span class="dot-red"></span><strong>Flavored coffee drinks</strong> — cream is fine, sugar and syrups are not. A flavored latte can run 300–400 calories.</li>
      <li><span class="dot-red"></span><strong>Juice and sports drinks</strong> — essentially sugar water. A 16 oz glass of OJ has nearly as much sugar as a Coke.</li>
      <li><span class="dot-red"></span><strong>Eating past 8pm</strong> — late eating spikes insulin when your body is winding down. Keep dinner the last meal of the day.</li>
      <li><span class="dot-red"></span><strong>Skipping protein at any meal</strong> — hunger comes back fast and you overeat later. Always anchor your meal to a protein source.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="section-heading">Good habits to build</div>
  <div style="background: var(--white); border: 1px solid var(--gray-border); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: 4px 18px; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
    <ul class="good-list">
      <li><span class="dot-green"></span><strong>Drink one glass of water before lunch and dinner</strong> — reduces false hunger signals and prevents overeating.</li>
      <li><span class="dot-green"></span><strong>One Liquid IV in the morning</strong> — good use of the product. Gets you hydrated early, replaces electrolytes lost overnight.</li>
      <li><span class="dot-green"></span><strong>Flavor water naturally</strong> — cucumber/lemon in a pitcher, sparkling water (Topo Chico, La Croix), or a small splash of 100% juice.</li>
      <li><span class="dot-green"></span><strong>Sleep 7–8 hours</strong> — sleep is when fat loss happens hormonally. Cortisol rises with poor sleep and directly drives belly fat storage.</li>
      <li><span class="dot-green"></span><strong>Walk on rest days</strong> — 30–45 min walks on Saturday/Sunday keep your metabolism active without adding workout stress.</li>
      <li><span class="dot-green"></span><strong>Add reps or time each week</strong> — progressive overload is the difference between a plateau at week 4 and continued results at month 6.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="section-heading">Age-specific notes for 47+</div>
  <div class="info-grid">
    <div class="info-card">
      <h3>Warm up fully</h3>
      <p>Never skip the warm-up. Joint prep matters far more at 47 than it did at 27. Five minutes now prevents weeks of setback from a tweaked knee or shoulder.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="info-card">
      <h3>Cortisol management</h3>
      <p>Stress hormone cortisol drives belly and love handle fat specifically. Sleep, rest days, and not overtraining are as important as the workouts themselves.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="info-card">
      <h3>Realistic pace</h3>
      <p>1–1.5 lbs per week is the right target. At that rate, 30 lbs takes 5–6 months. That's the pace where you keep the muscle and don't bounce back.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="info-card">
      <h3>Know your blood pressure</h3>
      <p>Carrying belly weight at 47 means it's worth knowing your BP numbers. High sodium (from Liquid IV overuse, soy sauce, processed foods) is the main dietary lever on BP.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

